From: lxh <lmhtq1991@gmail.com>
Date: Fri, 29 May 2026 10:55:00 +0800
Subject: [PATCH] Phase C-6 fix #26: cap-BLR unblocks the trampoline (L25 SOLVED)

THE KEY INSIGHT: HotSpot's Assembler::blr emits the INTEGER `blr Xn`
(0xd63f0000-family / branch_reg with opc=0b0001) which only updates
PC within the CURRENT PCC bounds — it does NOT install a new PCC. So
when a codecache stub (PCC bounds = [code_cache]) branches to a cap
pointing into libjvm.so .text, the PC moves but PCC bounds stay at
the codecache, and the very first instruction fetch at the new PC
faults PROT_CHERI_BOUNDS. This is exactly why codecache-internal BLRs
worked (PCC bounds happened to cover the target) but the trampoline
BLR to libjvm.so failed.

Fix: Morello capability BLR `blr Cn` (0xC2C23000 | Rn<<5, verified vs
Morello clang) installs Cn as the NEW PCC and seals the return addr
into CLR as a sentry. Added cap_blr/cap_br helpers in
macroAssembler_aarch64.hpp and switched call_VM_leaf_base's CHERI
path to cap_blr.

RESULT: the trampoline now executes correctly. cap_trampoline_dispatch
runs in libjvm.so (PCC = [0x4170d000, 0x421c6000]), looks up the
runtime fn by id, and C++-calls it. We land inside
MethodCounters::allocate_with_exception and execute dozens of real
runtime instructions — crossing from codecache stub code into
libjvm.so C++ runtime for the first time.

Next fault is a DIFFERENT class entirely: a tag-propagation issue
(PROT_CHERI_TAG) where a methodHandle's Method* field reads back
tag-0. That's normal libjvm.so C++ execution debugging, not the
codecache↔libjvm.so boundary problem L25 represented.

L25 is SOLVED. The trampoline architecture (patch 0099) + cap-BLR
(this) together bridge the codecache↔runtime boundary.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>

